Manage Users and Groups in Linux

Create users
useradd -m user1


-m creates home directory.

useradd -m user2
useradd -m user3
useradd -m user4


or in one go:

for u in user2 user3 user4; do useradd -m "$u"; done

useradd -m -e 2026-01-31 -c "User Five" -s /bin/ksh user5
Creates user5 with expiry date, full name, and shell.
Check user info

tail /etc/passwd
Shows last 10 entries.

usermod -c "User Two" user2
Adds comment to user2.

usermod -e 2026-01-08 user3
Sets expiry for user3.

cat /etc/shadow | tail -n 10
Check password/expiry info.

Delete user
userdel -r user10

----------------------------------------------------------------------------
Removes user + home directory.

Groups
groupadd groupA

for g in groupB groupC groupD groupE; do groupadd "$g"; done

groupmod -g 4000 groupD
Change GID for groupD.

tail -n 10 /etc/group
Check last 10 groups.

-----
Add user to groups
usermod -aG groupA user1


Verify:
id user1

usermod -aG groupA,groupB user2


Remove user2 from groupB but keep in groupA:
usermod -G groupA user2

Delete group
usermod -aG groupE user5
id user5
groupdel groupE


Verify:
tail -n 10 /etc/group
tail -n 10 /etc/passwd


groupE deleted, but user5 still exists.
